<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/427C8A9E-64D8-4940-8911-953B4A177A75"><gtr:id>427C8A9E-64D8-4940-8911-953B4A177A75</gtr:id><gtr:name>School of Oriental &amp; African Studies</gtr:name><gtr:department>Development Studies</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Thornhaugh Street</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Russell Square</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>WC1H 0XG</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/427C8A9E-64D8-4940-8911-953B4A177A75"><gtr:id>427C8A9E-64D8-4940-8911-953B4A177A75</gtr:id><gtr:name>School of Oriental &amp; African Studies</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Thornhaugh Street</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Russell Square</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>WC1H 0XG</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/A2045412-D4B1-456A-A8AC-3463732FBFCB"><gtr:id>A2045412-D4B1-456A-A8AC-3463732FBFCB</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Justin</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Leonard</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Pearce</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FI031456%2F1"><gtr:id>77999CBC-D6F5-401A-9BA7-082F4DFB0423</gtr:id><gtr:title>Conflict, identity and political mobilisation: the case of the Angolan civil war</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I031456/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>During the ESRC postdoctoral fellowship Justin Pearce will publish articles and begin a book based on his doctoral research, concerning the Angolan civil war between the MPLA government and the UNITA rebels, from before independence in 1975 until the end of the conflict in 2002. It examines political relationships in the context of the civil war: how the MPLA and UNITA attempted by persuasion and by coercion to create a relationship with the people in the territories they controlled, and people?s response to this in terms of their own political identities and behaviour.&lt;br />&lt;br />The book will provide a history of political mobilisation in the Angolan Central Highlands from the late colonial period through the civil war. At the theoretical level it will revise the assumptions underlying previous accounts of civil conflict and of post-colonial state building, emphasising parallels in the processes of mobilisation by states and by rebels. Journal articles will include:&lt;br />&lt;br />&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>an analysis of the accord that ended the Angolan civil war in 2002&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>a history of the months before Angolan independence&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>the nature of political identity and belonging in the Angolan war&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>the siege of Kuito (1993-1994)&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>contemporary politics and continuities with the past.&lt;/li>

&lt;/ul>

